AGI - The debate on the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-25/ appeal-stoltenberg-use-Ukrainian-russia-26520697/" > the words of the Secretary-General of NATO</a>, Jens Stoltenberg>, who urged allies to remove the restrictions that prevent Kiev from using weapons all the military material we send in Ukraine must be used to protect Ukraine within the Ukrainian territory and we control this use. We are not at war with Russia and will not send Italian soldiers to fight."
&nbsp;
"It is not for Stoltenberg to decide, it is not his competence," said the vice-premier who arrived in Brussels for the Foreign Council, "sometimes needs a little more caution. It is his opinion, but NATO decisions are always taken together. However, our position is clear: our weapons are used within the Ukrainian territory." A "prudence" <a href="https://www.agi.it/politica/news/2024-05-26/meloni-referendum-premierato-stoltenberg-guerra-ucraina-russia-26534517/" > evoded yesterday</a> also by the President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni>, in his statements to "In half an hour". "This gentleman is dangerous, who can stop him," says the Leghist leader, Matteo Salvini>. The high official's statements "do not make a good effect," notes Cecilia Strada> del Pd, saying that he agrees with the call for caution of the Minister of Defense, Guido Crosetto>.
<h2>" Ukrainians have their hands tied"</h2>
In a speech to the Parliamentary Assembly of the Covenant in Sofia, Stoltenberg nevertheless relaunched, stating that "it is &nbsp; now the time to consider the elimination of some of the existing restrictions. We see that in the Kharkiv area the front line and the border are almost in the same place, and Ukraine cannot attack military targets on the Russian territory." "This means that Ukrainians have their hands tied up. They are attacked by Russian territory and cannot respond because there are restrictions on the use of weapons," he added, "it is for allies to decide on the restrictions on weapons they provide to Ukraine. It's not a NATO decision. It is a decision made by individual allies. And they are making different decisions: some have no restrictions, others have different. Some allies have removed the restrictions, others have not. My message is to reconsider these restrictions. Because when they're too many, we tie a hand of Ukrainian forces behind our backs. But it's a national decision, it's not NATO."
&nbsp;
"When this war began, in February 2022, most experts feared that Russia would take control of Ukraine within weeks. That didn't happen. The Ukrainians were able to free almost 50% of the occupied territories from Russia. And they were able to inflict heavy losses on Russian invaders. That said, we have to do more. Because the reality is that what we have done so far is not enough and we see some gaps in providing support. That is why I ask all the allies to do more," said NATO Secretary-General at a press point with Bulgarian Prime Minister Dimitar Glavchev.
&nbsp;
Stoltenberg recalled that "Ukraine has the right to self-defense, defends its territory and on the basis of international law, the right to defence includes the right to strike legitimate military objectives outside Ukraine. It is part of the self-defense and we see it clearly in the battle of Kharkiv> because Russian forces are on Russian territory and attack beyond borders, in Ukrainian territory. The front line corresponds more or less to the border line. And if you can't attack Russian forces across the border, it means you reduce the ability of Ukrainian forces to defend yourself. Because the Russians can hit without getting counterattacks." &nbsp;
<h2>"NATO is not part of the conflict"</h2>
"What we do in Ukraine does not make NATO part of the conflict. Basically, NATO has two objectives: One is supporting Ukraine and the other is preventing the escalation of conflict beyond Ukraine. We do not want a large-scale conflict between Russia and NATO," Stoltenberg said, "NATO does not seek conflict with Russia, we do not have plans to deploy NATO troops in Ukraine or send aerial capabilities into Ukrainian airspace."
&nbsp;
"We do not see any imminent threat of armed attacks against any NATO ally. Obviously with the war in Ukraine and the instability in the Baltic it was necessary to increase our vigilance and our presence, both on the ground and in the air, to ensure to be ready to react in case of need", he concluded.

