AGI -&nbsp; At least 40 deaths the Israeli bombing budget on a field of unrwa displaced people in the north-western part of Rafah>, south of Gaza, according to what has been reported by Hamas>, who condemned the "horrible massacre". According to the authorities of the Strip, most victims are women and children.&nbsp; Very harsh words came also from the Palestinian National Authority > in West Bank which accused Israeli troops of "taking deliberately" the tents of the displaced. Medesima accusation was launched by Egypt who spoke of "demonstrated attack", urging Israel to stop military operations at Rafah.
&nbsp;
Qatar has expressed "the concern that attacks will complicate ongoing mediation efforts and will block an agreement for an immediate and permanent ceasefire." The emirate, who is working together with Egypt and the United States to relaunch talks in stalls for weeks, urged the international community to act urgently to prevent Israel from "to implement its plans for forced displacement of Palestinians from the city, which has become a refuge for hundreds of thousands" of people.
<h2> Two senior officials from Hamas</h2>
Israel has announced that the target of the raid was Yassin Rabia, responsible for the activities of the Palestinian group in the West Bank, along with Commander Khaled Nagar, both killed. From Idf the military prosecutor, General Yifat Tomer Yerushalmi, called "very serious" the night attack on Rafah and assured that an investigation is underway. "Idf regrets any damage suffered by non-combatants during the war," he added. No comment from the White House >that in the night it was limited to making known that it is aware of the news about the attack and is collecting more information.
&nbsp;
Yesterday, for the first time since January, the central region of Israel was targeted, including Tel Aviv, with rocket launch from Rafah. It was a "response to the Zionist massacres against civilians", they claimed the brigades Ezzedin al-Qassam. According to the Israeli military spokesman, Daniel Hagari, "Hamas launched these rockets from two mosques to Rafah". The militant group urged the Palestinians to "lift and march" against employment.
&nbsp;
Last Friday, the International Court of Justice (Icj) ruled in the case promoted by South Africa against Israel, ordering the Jewish State to immediately end the operation to Rafah and allow the entry of aid through the vessels. For its part, Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu> reiterated his intention to carry out the Israeli offensive, underlining his firm opposition to the demands of Hamas' leader in Gaza, Yahya Sinwar, who "continue to demand the end of the war, the withdrawal of the Idf from the Strip and the maintenance of Hamas, so that it can still and still carry out the atrocities of October 7". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2>Tel Aviv: News leaks on negotiation damage hostages
Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu denied Sunday the leaks of news concerning the negotiation for the release of hostages in exchange for a truce, saying that these indiscretions "do nothing but strengthen the position of Hamas". The Prime Minister said that the leaks of news "damag the families of the hostages and delay their release".
&nbsp;
The reaction, reported by the Israeli press, was widespread following the news that one of the negotiators, the Conservative General Nitzan Alon, believes that the mandate is not wide enough to achieve results and would have claimed that the current government will never accept a hostage agreement. On the contrary, we read in a statement of the Prime Minister's office, "Netanyahu repeatedly gave the negotiating team a broad mandate to free our abducts."
<h2>Borrell: relaunch of the EU mission
"I will put on the table a proposal to relaunch our Eubam Rafah mission on the civil system of borders, if it will be useful", announced the High Representative of the EU for Foreign Policy, Josep Borrell>, upon his arrival to the Foreign Council. "We were asked to do it. If we can, we will. But considering that everything must go in the direction of making the Palestinian Authority take responsibility on Gaza," he said. "Today the political free path is awaited, then there will be technical work to be done," said Borrell.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"We must respect the work of the International Criminal Court. We must respect the work of this institution and let the tribunal, without intimidation, decide what it thinks of this initiative of the public ministry. Unfortunately, it's not. The prosecutor and the court were strongly intimidated and accused of anti-Semitism. As always happens for anyone who does something that does not like the Netanyahu government," said the EU High Representative for Foreign Policy.
&nbsp;
"I think that the prosecution of anti-Semitism against the prosecutor of the International Criminal Court is totally unacceptable. Defining the anti-Semitic Court is too heavy. It's too important to use it on these occasions," he said. "And then there is the most important and even more important thing is the judgment of the International Court of Justice, which is the hub of international justice to act above the national level, is at the heart of the United Nations Charter. And here too we must express not only respect, but call for the implementation of the Court's decision. And now, unfortunately, what we have seen in the immediate hours is that Israel continues the military action that had been asked to stop. It also applies to Hamas who launches rockets against Israel. So both parties do not respect the Court's ruling," he added.
<div </div
<h2> Spain, Ireland and Norway will recognise the State of Palestine
&nbsp;"Today our three countries, Ireland, Norway and Spain, will live a historical day that will surely approach the goal we all want: to achieve peaceful and secure coexistence in the Middle East," said Spanish Foreign Minister Manuel Albares, announcing the official recognition of the State of Palestine.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Albares then condemned a video published by his Israeli counterpart Israel Katz entitled "Hamas: Grazie Spagna" in which images of the Spanish flag and flamenco dancers are combined with spezzoni of the atrocities made by Hamas militiamen on October 7.
&nbsp;
"We will not fall into provocations. The video is scandalous and execrable," said Albares, stressing that "it is scandalous because the whole world knows, including my colleague in Israel, that Spain has condemned Hamas' actions since the first moment. It is execrable for the use of one of these symbols of Spanish culture."
&nbsp;

