AGI - Papua New Guinea informed the UN that more than 2,000 people were buried living in a huge swirl of mud and rocks that overwhelmed a remote village on the highlands. "The landslide lives more than 2,000 people and has caused severe destruction," reads in the letter sent by the National Center for disasters to the United Nations office in Port Moresby. On Sunday evening Serhan Aktoprak, an official of the UN immigration agency based in Port Moresby had spoken of 150 destroyed houses and 670 dead.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The Secretary-General of the UN said "profoundly saddened" by the news of the hundreds of lives lost in the gigantic sorting that struck a village in Papua New Guinea. "The United Nations - Secretary Antonio Guterres added, through the spokesman - and his partners are supporting the government's efforts. We are ready to offer further help at this difficult time." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Chinese President Xi Jinping said he was "victed" by the news and offered help to the insular Pacific nation. "China is ready to provide assistance," added Xi in a letter. The UN invited member countries to a meeting on emergency aid through Zoom at 10:00 tomorrow local time (two at night in Italy), said the French embassy in Port Moresby.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

