AGI -&nbsp; The 27 EU countries are preparing for the next electoral expiry of June, but the spectrum of abstention is weighing on all. The topic was discussed in one of the panel of the Trento Economy Festival, together with Jaume Duch, Director-General of the Communication DG of the European Parliament, Lorenzo Ferrari, Editorial Coordinator of the Balkan Observatory and Caucasus-Transeuropa and Luciana Maruta, journalist of the digital magazine Divergente, coordinated by Michela Finizio, Journalist of "Il Sole 24 Ore".
&nbsp;
A broad spectrum survey conducted throughout Europe by these subjects, starting from Divergente, analysed the reasons for the non-vote, bringing out some trends. The future of European democracy would seem primarily linked to the welfare of the population. The countries or regions with more astensionism are those with older people, with higher illiteracy rates and above all with lower incomes. The reasons for the non-vote, however, would be more linked to a general disillusionment towards politics, rather than to Europe in a strict sense. But there are also reasons to be optimistic. In fact, the rate of participation in the European votes is constantly growing: in 2014 voted 42% of voters. 51% in 2019. In the next elections the polls show a participation that could approach 60%.
&nbsp;
The survey conducted by the Portuguese magazine Divergente, together with the Trentino Observatory on the Balkans and Caucasus-Transeuropa and the Sun 24 Ore &nbsp; has processed a large amount of data that were then made available to the information bodies, for a comparative approach between the different EU countries. But the investigation has also been thoroughly investigated in the reasons for abstention in the most critical areas, often rural ones, trying to hear as many people as possible, to bring out a "truth" portrait of the phenomenon.
&nbsp;
Among the evidence emerged, the correlation between income (low) and astensionism is very strong. That between abstentionism and education is less. &nbsp; Where abstentionism is stronger it has emerged that people consider Europe far away. A criticism expressed in rural areas was also that the European bureaucracy to access funds is too complex. Also in rural areas, European electoral campaigns penetrate little, and so also the media. And again: many citizens would have something to express, but they are convinced that they would be ignored.
&nbsp;
For Douch, in Trento as spokesman for the European Parliament, it emerged however that we vote more when people feel that the vote will change things. Otherwise participation is lower. There are countries where information about Europe comes little in both urban and rural areas. But it is also true that there are areas where information is more widespread, also thanks to social media. In the new generations the confidence in traditional media, which are the ones that interface more with European institutions, is in decline. Young people trust more than influencers, content cretor and so on.
&nbsp;
But phenomena such as Brexit, Covid, war in Ukraine have made the media speak more than Europe. Perhaps this also explains why the polls on participation in the next elections see the trend of voters growing, average of 5%. This growth, however, has already happened in the past even if in a differentiated way. &nbsp; In 2019 participation grew mainly in the young electorate (which in the past was tendingly abstentionist). At that time the theme of climate change had exploded, and this perhaps helped. In the countries of Eastern Europe, at first it was voted much less than in Western Europe (where the rate of participation has always been more than 50%). A justification given by citizens was: first for us to vote was mandatory, and then nothing changed. Now that we are free we can choose not to vote.
&nbsp;
The three first reasons in abstentionism in 2019 did not really have much to do with Europe but with politics in general. The first reason: disappointment towards politics. Second, disinterest in politics. The third: voting is useless. These reasons are difficult to “correct” only with information. They express a more general discomfort. Voting regulations also do not help. Vote compulsory in places of residence is often an impediment. Also: many today vote 10 times a day with the mobile phone, why not experiment with electronic voting mode?
&nbsp;
The polls say this time will vote 70% of voters. We can therefore think that realistically we will approach 60%. But why vote? Because the world is increasingly complex, and this complexity calls into question not only nations but also Europe. And then because the insecurity generated by the war in Ukraine has heavy consequences especially in some countries, closer to the front. This suggests that voting in the countries in Eastern Europe will grow.
&nbsp;

